Professional Summary

•Innovative researcher with solid understanding of the process of drug development and Product Quality/CMC evaluation and review

•Advanced background in cancer and public health research 

•Committed champion of health equity with diverse expertise in breast, lung, and colon cancer

•Excellent communicator and enthusiastic collaborator with ability to design, generate, analyze, interpret, troubleshoot, and report complex data

•Experience conducting toxicity and efficacy studies with in vitro, in vivo, and in silico models

•Served as career development co-chair of a fellow’s activity board, peer-reviewer for JAMA Oncology journal, and peer-mentor to 1st year cohort of post-doc fellows
fullName: Courtney D. Dill, PhD, MSCR, MSBR

currentPositions.description:
Track 4: Cancer Prevention Product Research and Review: This fellowship, in partnership with the NCI Cancer Prevention Fellowship Program, trains individuals in aspects of the cancer prevention drug, biologic, or device development processes, including their application to study populations, to facilitate the movement of novel approaches from the bench to the community.

Research 
•	Led collaboration between FDA Office of Pharmaceutical Quality (OPQ), FDA Office of New Drugs (OND), and the Center for Disease Control (CDC), examining the genomic profile of colon cancer cell lines to identify markers of drug resistance 

•	Performed literature review, data management, data cleaning, alignment, and downstream analysis including differential expression, Ingenuity Pathway analysis, and DAVID gene set enrichment via precision FDA tool

•	Presented monthly updates to working group members, and led write-up of 1st author manuscript in preparation

Regulatory Activity 
The Office of Pharmaceutical Quality (OPQ) regulates a broad array of biotechnology products (e.g., recombinant proteins, monoclonal antibodies, bispecific antibodies, antibody-drug conjugates, biosimilars, combination products. 

•	Knowledge of Good Clinical Practice (GCP), Good Laboratory Practice (GLP), Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP), International Council for harmonization of Technical Requirements of Pharmaceuticals for Human use guidelines (ICH)

•	Knowledge and use of electronic common technical document (eCTD) and Document Archiving Reporting and Regulatory Tracking System (DARRTS)

•	Knowledge and skills in Product Quality/Chemistry Manufacturing and Control (CMC) evaluation and review of pharmaceutical biologics

•	Evaluate and review INDs and their respective amendments and supplements

•	Served as primary assessor (PA) on INDs

message.text:
✨NCI Director’s Award Celebration 

Today I was one of several CPFP fellows that received a NCI Merit Award for outstanding mentorship in the Cancer Prevention Fellowship Program.

The award is in recognition of service as mentors for growing professional opportunities, expanding orientation/onboarding activities, and promoting wellness for new fellows.

And me and Alexandra Harris  jumped on the opportunity to take a photo with the new NCI Director, W. Kimryn Rathmell!

Highlights from my 1st #ASPO2024 Annual Meeting!

Saw the Chicago river dyed green for St. Patrick’s Day. 

Attended my 1st conference with my #NCI preceptor, Hormuzd Katki, who taught me how to build cancer risk prediction models and finally got a picture of the 2 of us.

Gave my 2nd ever national talk.

Co-hosted one of the largest #CPFP Alumni mixers.

Supported A fellow NCI fellow at her first poster presentation.
If you’re attending the ASPO Annual Meeting today, please attend my flash talk at 10:30am.

The NCI’s Cancer Prevention Fellowship Program (https://CPFP.cancer.gov) is excited to announce that CPFP fellow, Dr. Courtney Dill, was invited to give a 5 minute flash talk at the 48th American Society of Preventive Oncology Annual Meeting, to be held March 17-19, 2024, in Chicago. She will present her abstract, Association of Combined Polygenic Risk Score and Environmental Score with Risk of Recurrent Adenoma in the PLCO and PPT cohorts, on Tuesday, March 19, 2024
at 10:30 AM. 

Association of Combined Polygenic Risk Score and Environmental Score with Risk of Recurrent Adenoma in the PLCO and PPT cohorts

Session: Looking Back, Thinking Forward 4: Precision Prevention
Session Time: 10:30 AM – 11:15 AM

ingestedContentSummary.description: Spelman College will be the first HBCU to offer cosmetic chemistry as a concentration and minor, allowing for more Black women in beauty.
ingestedContentSummary.title: Spelman College First HBCU To Offer Cosmetic Chemistry Program, A Win For Women In STEM

message.text:
Yes, yes and YES!! I am SO proud of my alma mater for building out this program.

I am a firm believer that diversity in the lab translates to diversity on the shelves! 

The importance of having Black chemists at the forefront of cosmetic product formulation cannot be overstated. For too long, the beauty industry has operated with a one-size-fits-all approach, frequently overlooking the unique needs of people of color. This oversight isn’t just a matter of shades and pigments but a gap in understanding the complex needs of different skin and hair types at a molecular level. Their expertise is crucial in addressing specific concerns, such as hyperpigmentation, scalp health, and hair and skin texture variations, which are often neglected in mainstream beauty. 

Not to mention, this shift has the potential to address and rectify historical disparities in the beauty industry, providing opportunities for wealth creation, leadership, and innovation within Black communities. This is more than just as a nod to diversity, it’s as a commitment to excellence, innovation, and representation.

I love it, and I’m so excited for this upcoming wave of chemists, manufacturers, lobbyists, industry leaders, entrepreneurs and regulators!
